@article{Xu2016,
abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} Wetlands are the largest global natural methane (CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater}) source, and emissions between 50 and 70°{\textless}span class="thinspace"{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}N latitude contribute 10–30{\textless}span class="thinspace"{\textgreater}{\textless}/span{\textgreater}{\%} to this source. Predictive capability of land models for northern wetland CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} emissions is still low due to limited site measurements, strong spatial and temporal variability in emissions, and complex hydrological and biogeochemical dynamics. To explore this issue, we compare wetland CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} emission predictions from the Community Land Model 4.5 (CLM4.5-BGC) with site- to regional-scale observations. A comparison of the CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} fluxes with eddy flux data highlighted needed changes to the model's estimate of aerenchyma area, which we implemented and tested. The model modification substantially reduced biases in CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} emissions when compared with CarbonTracker CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} predictions. CLM4.5 CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} emission predictions agree well with growing season (May–September) CarbonTracker Alaskan regional-level CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} predictions and site-level observations. However, CLM4.5 underestimated CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} emissions in the cold season (October–April). The monthly atmospheric CH{\textless}sub{\textgreater}4{\textless}/sub{\textgreater} mole fraction enhancements due to wetland emissions are also assessed